      "role": "user",
      "content": "it just doesnt feel like a temporary thing. like, there is no \"after.\" i look at my life and i just see a void. people say things get better, but",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear you, and I want to validate that the feeling of a permanent void is incredibly terrifying when it feels so real. When the \"after\" seems non-existent, it's easy to feel like you're trapped in a loop with no exit, which is a heavy burden to carry alone.\n\nPlease remember that while the pain feels eternal right now, your brain is often trying to protect you from the intensity of the loss by convincing you that nothing will ever change again. This isn't necessarily a prediction of the future; it's a symptom of the current storm.\n\n*   **The \"No After\" Feeling:** When grief is this deep, it can feel like the ground has simply disappeared beneath you. It's a very isolating sensation, but it doesn't mean the ground isn't there, just that you can't see it yet.\n*   **The \"Nothing Gets Better\" Narrative:** Sometimes, the mind creates a story where the end is the only truth, but that story is often just a reflection of the current darkness, not the actual future.\n*   **The Void:** A void is just an empty space, and while it feels cold and silent, it is also a place where new things can eventually settle",
      "source": "target",
